{"annotations": [{"id": ["CHEBI:305790"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "thyroxine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9989690780639648, "span": {"begin": 24, "end": 33}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014284"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "triiodothyronine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991390705108643, "span": {"begin": 43, "end": 59}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6528"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NIS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9961661100387573, "span": {"begin": 84, "end": 87}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7173"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TPO", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9826976656913757, "span": {"begin": 92, "end": 95}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7038"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "iodinated thyroglobulin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8219393491744995, "span": {"begin": 120, "end": 143}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7038"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Tg", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9987154006958008, "span": {"begin": 145, "end": 147}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "thyroid follicles", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.4707644283771515, "span": {"begin": 178, "end": 195}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7253"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "thyroid stimulating hormone", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9985702037811279, "span": {"begin": 299, "end": 326}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:10194", "79896"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "TSH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9932936429977417, "span": {"begin": 328, "end": 331}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7038"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Tg", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 394, "end": 396}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7054"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "TH", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 401, "end": 403}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "thyrocyte", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.867324948310852, "span": {"begin": 512, "end": 521}}], "text": "Thyroid hormones (THs), thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3) are synthesized by NIS and TPO in the thyroid gland as iodinated thyroglobulin (Tg) and stored in the colloid of thyroid follicles across vertebrates. Secretion from the follicle into serum is a multi-step process. The first involves thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) stimulation of the separation of the peptide linkage between Tg and TH. The next steps involve endocytosis of colloid, fusion of the endosome with the basolateral membrane of the thyrocyte, and finally release of TH into blood. More detailed descriptions of this process can be found in reviews by Braverman and Utiger (2012) and Zoeller et al. (2007).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:38:11 +0000 2026"}